<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">National Federation of Retail Newsagents </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt">[PCC Progress 11]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1. The National Federation of Retail Newsagents (NFRN) would like to thank the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Home Affairs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Committee for the invitation to make a written submission on the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Police and Crime C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommissioners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2. The NFRN is one of Europe’s largest trade associations, representing over 16,000 fee paying members from approximately 18,000 independent newsagents and convenience stores across the UK, Channel Islands and the Republic of Ireland. We are a membership led organisation that is democratically structured; policy is made by annual conference and its implementation is overseen by National Council.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3. The NFRN assis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts the independent retailer to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">compete more effectively in today’s highly competitive market through the provision of practical help and assistance, commercial support, deals and buying opportunities, training, expert</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ise and services. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t also represents its members’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> interests at governmental and p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arliamentary level, as well as within the news and magazine industry. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#c00000; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General Remarks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The NFRN understands the importance of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> role of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to both the police and local communities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5. With this in mind, the NFRN is working towards its aim of meeting all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PCCs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over the course of the coming year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6. NFRN engage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment with PC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cs has already started. We recently wrote a letter to all PCCs regar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ding our concerns about shoplifting and the impact it ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s on our members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’ businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Going forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> will continue to engage with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> through regular contact and our newsletter, to keep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> informed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> about the key crime issues facing the independent retail sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">7. However it is important to note that one year is not long enough to be able to fully judge the performance of PCCs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. In our submission to the committee’s inquiry, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the NFRN will focus on the two following areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, from the Federation’s perspective of their handling of the issue of shoplifting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and anti-social behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effectiveness of commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within their police force area</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Declaration of Interest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to engage with PCCs on beh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">alf of our members, we have no further</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relationship with them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within their police force area</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">10. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> since c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommissioners were elected, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there have been a number of notable achievements delivered by various PCCs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">11. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e welcomed news that the PCC for West Yorkshire Mark Burns-Williamson had launched a petition with the intention of persuading the government to ensure that the funds generated from seized criminal assets are spent on community and anti-crime initiatives in the same areas where the crimes were committed</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">12. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a number of PC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cs have launched community crime funds in their areas to help </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tackle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> problems. PCC for Avon and Somerset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sue Mountstevens</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has allocated £2.4m to various organisations in the area to help reduce crime and disorder. The fund will also provide support for victims of crime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a move supported by the NFRN</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">13. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, there is still room for improvement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in terms of the effectiveness with which commissioners are reducing crime and delivering an effective police service within thei</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r areas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, the way in which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> business crime, specifically shoplifting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, is dealt with is of concern to the Federation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’s members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Discussions with our members and recent media reports have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> raised concerns amongst the NFRN that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shoplifting is not being </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dealt with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> seriously enough by police and police and crime commissioners.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">15. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An investigation by the Birmingham Mail for example, discovered that police had failed to investigate or record more than 60% of shoplifting incidents that had taken place in Birmingham’s city centre</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">16. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, it was reported in August 2013 that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Hammersmith and Fulham police</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had dropped a proposal to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not arrest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> those who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> shoplift goods under £50</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst it is fortunate the proposal was not adopted, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the NFRN considers that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it should not have been considered in the first place as it would have undermined the businesses of our members.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">17. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he NFRN appreciate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that PCCs are not in operational control of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">police; however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> they do set their priorities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Therefore we feel that more work needs to be done to ensure that this important issue is not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">allowed to slip down the policing agenda in terms of performance.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">18. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Another issue where improvements could be made is anti-social behaviour against retail workers more generally.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">19. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unfortunately, newsagents and convenience stores are easy targets for such behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in light of their late opening hours and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relatively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> few members of staff on duty in comparison to the large supermarkets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a survey we conducted recently of our membership, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">35.7% of respondents had been a victim of crime or anti-social behaviour </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the last 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">21. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, research published recently by the Union </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of Shop Distributive and Allied Workers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Usdaw)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> revealed that of their shop worker respondents, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1 in 5 report verbal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">abuse on a daily or weekly basis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, almost 1 in 10 report a threat of violence at least once a month.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">22. A survey carried out for Independent Retail News also showed that the number of independent retailers who had been a victim of violent crime had increased from 8%in 2010 to 15% in 2011.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Anti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-social behaviour, violence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and threatening behaviour </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ontinuing to blight our members’ livelihoods.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">24</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are appreciative of work already done on this issue by PCC’s. For example, in October 2013 the NFRN was pleased to learn that Commissioners had joined Chief Constables to support a campaign week seeking to tackle the problem</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">25</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However in light of this continuing problem, we feel that more attention needs to be placed on the issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to help protect retailers and their staff from this behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">26</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NFRN will focus its response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to this question on its knowledge of the priority PCCs place on the issue of shoplifting.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">27</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As noted previously in this submission, the Federation wrote to all PCCs asking them to clarify their approach to this form of crime. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">28</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he responses we have received from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Police and Crime Commissioners regarding shoplifting, have all sought to reassure the NFRN that the issue of shoplifting remains high in the list of policing priorities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">29</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In practice, PCCs have gone to varying lengths in their promotion of policing priorities. Whilst some have simply provided assurance that they understand the importance of the issue, others have taken steps to demonstrate that this is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">truly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the case.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">30</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clive Grunshaw, PCC for Lancashire advised us that a business crime lead for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Constabulary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had been appointed and that he personally holds the Chief Constable to account for performance in this area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">31</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, Bill Longmore the PCC for West Mercia revealed that he was in the process of developing a Business Crime strategy for both West Mercia and Warwickshire police and Essex PCC Nick Alston </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">held a business crime forum to discuss the issue.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">32</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, the issue is not being as demonstrably prioritised in other areas of the country. Mark Burns-Williamson OBE, PCC for West Yorkshire recognised the importance of the issue but admitted it was “not specifically a priority within the Police and Crime Plan”. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">33</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is evident that the effectiveness of PCCs in promoting this issue varies considerably in different areas.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">34</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The NFRN appreciates the hard work many PCCs have put into dealing with this matter but would encourage all commissioners to do the same, in order for this type of behaviour to be tackled effectively. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">35</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would welcome the issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of shoplifting and anti-social behaviour becoming priorities in all Police and Crime Plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the NFRN will seek to engage with PCCs as they develop these plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:20pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:22pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/04/police-crime-commissioners-five-best-worst-ideas"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/04/police-crime-commissioners-five-best-worst-ideas</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.avonandsomerset-pcc.gov.uk/News-and-Events/News-Archive/2013/May/PCCs-24m-fund-to-tackle-crime-and-disorder.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.avonandsomerset-pcc.gov.uk/News-and-Events/News-Archive/2013/May/PCCs-24m-fund-to-tackle-crime-and-disorder.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p st